<main>

<article>
<h2>On Web Standards and Longevity</h2>
<p><em>February 2026</em></p>

<p>The web is built on standards, yet many modern websites ignore them in favor of proprietary frameworks and bleeding-edge features. While innovation is important, we shouldn't sacrifice accessibility and longevity in the process.</p>

<p>A website built with proper semantic HTML, progressive CSS, and unobtrusive JavaScript can last for decades with minimal maintenance. Compare this to a site built with the framework-of-the-month, which might be obsolete in a few years. The web has a remarkable ability to maintain backward compatibility, but only if we use it wisely.</p>

<p>I believe in building websites that respect the user's choice of browser, device, and preferences. Not everyone has the latest hardware or wants to download megabytes of JavaScript just to read a blog post. Progressive enhancement is not just a technical approach; it's a philosophy of respect and inclusion.</p>
</article>

<hr>

<article>
<h2>The Joy of Vintage Computing</h2>
<p><em>January 2026</em></p>

<p>There's something special about working with vintage hardware. Whether it's a PowerPC Mac, a MIPS-based SGI workstation, or an old Sun SPARC server, these machines represent different eras of computing history and different approaches to solving problems.</p>

<p>Modern computing has largely converged on x86-64 and ARM architectures, but there was a time when diversity flourished. Each architecture had its strengths and unique characteristics. PowerPC was known for its elegant instruction set and performance. MIPS was favored in embedded systems and workstations. SPARC dominated enterprise computing.</p>

<p>Running these systems today isn't just nostalgia; it's a reminder that good design transcends specific technologies. Software that follows standards and doesn't make assumptions about the underlying hardware can run on diverse platforms. This is why I care about web standards and progressive enhancement. The principles that make a website work on a 1999 browser also make it work on unusual or future platforms.</p>
</article>

<hr>

<article>
<h2>Complexity vs. Simplicity</h2>
<p><em>December 2025</em></p>

<p>The modern web development ecosystem has become incredibly complex. Build tools, transpilers, bundlers, package managers, frameworks, state management libraries, CSS-in-JS, and countless other abstractions sit between the developer and the browser.</p>

<p>While these tools can be useful for large applications, they're often overkill for simple websites. Worse, they create fragility and maintenance burden. A simple HTML file from 1999 still works today. Will a React app from 2020 work in 2030 without updates?</p>

<p>I'm not against modern tools when they're appropriate, but I believe in choosing the simplest solution that meets the requirements. Sometimes that's a static HTML file. Sometimes it's a server-rendered application. Sometimes it's a full single-page application. The key is matching the tool to the problem, not the other way around.</p>

<p>This website is an exercise in simplicity. No build process, no dependencies, no framework lock-in. Just HTML, CSS, and a bit of JavaScript. It's easy to understand, easy to maintain, and will likely work for decades to come.</p>
</article>

<hr>

<article>
<h2>Open Standards and Open Source</h2>
<p><em>November 2025</em></p>

<p>The web succeeded because it was built on open standards that anyone could implement. HTML, CSS, JavaScript, HTTP, and other core technologies are documented specifications that don't belong to any single company. This openness enabled innovation and competition.</p>

<p>Today, we face pressures from proprietary platforms and walled gardens. While these platforms can provide convenience, they also create lock-in and reduce user freedom. I believe in supporting open standards and open source software whenever possible.</p>

<p>This doesn't mean rejecting all proprietary software, but it does mean being thoughtful about dependencies and vendor lock-in. It means choosing technologies that give users control and respect their freedom. It means contributing back to the commons when we can.</p>

<p>The web is one of humanity's great collaborative achievements. Let's keep it open, accessible, and free.</p>
</article>

